<DESC><![CDATA[Determined to uphold the essential values of individual freedom and equal treatment across all member nations,

Acknowledging GA#299&#146;s stated goal that &#147;freedom to make important decisions about one&#146;s life should not be unreasonably restricted&#148;,

Nonetheless, concerned that the resolution in question fails to achieve this goal, as the standards set for when an individual&#146;s personal freedom should be restricted go beyond the limit of what is reasonable, notably:

[list][*] The vague definition of &#147;very low intelligence&#148; in Article 2.1 allows governing bodies within a nation to oppress minority groups by declaring them legally incompetent according to a supposed standard of intelligence, which is especially worrying as there is no objective standard for intelligence or what constitutes &#147;very low intelligence&#148;, making it easy to manipulate this definition for malicious purposes;

[*] Article 2.2 specifies that the experts employed to measure compliance with these standards of intelligence must be &#147;allowed by the authorities to act&#148;, making it easy for said authorities to cherry-pick experts whose standards align with their own, even if the experts in question are acting fully autonomously as the target specifies;

[*] Article 4, when paired with the above definition and restrictions, allows governments to progressively set thresholds of legal allowance depending on intelligence, opening the door to various forms of discrimination;[/list]

Considering the resolution&#146;s incompetence at achieving its stated goals,

The General Assembly repeals &#147;Legal Competence&#148;.]]></DESC>
